<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Governors 2ndLd-Writethru a0831 02-21 1012</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Governors, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0831,980</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 8th graf pvs bgng, `Forty-four,' with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with Brubeck concert and new Dukakis comment; PICKS UP 10th graf
pvs bgng, `James C.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's governors appealed to the White
House Sunday for relief from 163 federal rules and regulations, and
heard a former governor call for a constitutional convention to
restore states' rights.
   New Hampshire Gov. John H. Sununu, opening the National
Governors' Association's winter meeting, said that the time has
come to press for a new division of authority between the states
and Washington.
   ``There has been an erosion of the fundamental balance struck
200 years ago in Philadelphia,'' Sununu, the NGA chairman, said at
a news conference before gaveling the first plenary session to
order.
   President Reagan, at a black-tie dinner for the governors Sunday
night, told the governors he envied the balanced-budget
requirements and line-item vetoes that many of them possess. ``Not
one of you would put up with the mess that we have here in
Washington at budget time,'' the president said.
   He also said he did not want to tie his successor's hands, but
expressed hope the next president would continue his tradition of
inviting the governors to the White House for dinner each year.
   Reagan exchanged toasts with Sununu, who said to Reagan, ``From
all of us to one of us: You did it your way. You did it well. God
speed.''
   The president planned to hold a working meeting with the
governors Monday to hear their concerns about regulations and other
matters.
   The Dave Brubeck Quartet brought the Reagans and their guests to
their feet with a concert that included W.C. Handy's ``St. Louis
Blues,'' Duke Ellington's ``Take the A Train'' and Brubeck's own
signature piece, ``Take Five.'' Brubeck was joined by his longtime
clarinet player Bill Smith, Randy Jones on drums and Brubeck's son,
Chris, on bass guitar and slide trombone.
   Reagan paid tribute to the jazz great, saying, ``It is magic. I
know it's sort of a cliche, but they not only don't write 'em that
way anymore, there aren't many around who play 'em anymore.''
   Forty-four governors were on hand for the affair, including
presidential hopeful Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, who quipped
about his visit to the White House, ``We've been looking it over,
checking it out. I've never lived over the store before.''
   Dukakis planned to depart the governors' meeting Monday to
resume campaigning in South Dakota and Minnesota, which hold a
primary and caucus respectively Feb. 23.
   James C. Miller III, director of the Office of Management and
Budget, told the governors the Reagan administration has carried
out nearly 50 of 80 recommendations the NGA made 16 months ago to
reduce red tape and administrative burdens on state and local
governments.
   Eyeing the new stack of 163 recommendations, Miller said,
``There's a lot more out there that needs to be done. It's hard to
do.'' But he added, ``There is no question that our federal system
of shared power between the federal and state governments ... is
healthier today than it has been in years.''
   The governors heard just the opposite from former Georgia Gov.
George Busbee, who warned, ``We are about one recession away from a
complete breakdown of domestic government in this country.''
   Busbee, an Atlanta lawyer who governed Georgia from 1975 to
1983, urged the governors to press for a constitutional convention
``to break the gridlock, sift through the blue smoke and mirrors
and restore a sense of order and accountability in American
government.''
   The federal government is raiding state and local revenue
sources and dumping unfunded mandates on the states, Busbee said,
and most of the presidential candidates are talking of new federal
initiatives in such areas of traditional state control as
education, welfare, economic development and criminal justice.
   ``Begging Congress or the administration to pay attention to
federalism is, in my opinion, a waste of time,'' said Busbee, a
Democrat. ``Governors and legislators are not treated much
differently from the `National Association of Ball Peen Hammer
Producers' _ except that (they) have a PAC (political action
committee) and you don't.''
   Even as Miller and Sununu exchanged thick lists of regulatory
reforms _ past, present and yet to come _ North Dakota Gov. George
A. Sinner was asking the OMB chief if he could stop a controversial
effort to force state Guananteed Student Loan agencies to send a
quarter-billion dollars of their reserves back to Washington.
   But Miller said that was part of the bipartisan
deficit-reduction measures Congress and the administration hammered
out late last year, and ``I don't think it's likely to be changed.''
   Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton said he thought the Reagan
administration was ``genuinely trying,'' but there are still too
many ``conflicting regulations that drive us nuts,'' especially in
health and welfare.
   ``It took us two years to get rejected for a waiver on welfare
reform,' Clinton complained.
   Reagan and the governors tried and failed to engineer a grand
swap of federal and state responsibilities in 1982, including a
complete federal takover of the Medicaid program. Reagan's
so-called ``new federalism'' foundered as the administration tried
to inflict simultaneous budget cuts on the programs.
   The theme of the governor's winter meeting, ``Restoring the
Balance: State Leadership for America's Future,'' is hardly new.
The governor's 1980 meeting centered on ``Restoring Balance to the
Federal System.''
   But Virginia Gov. Gerald L. Baliles said that does not gainsay
the importance of the new federalism initiative. ``Federalism is a
process. ...'' he said. ``It's a journey rather than a
destination.''
   The winter meeting runs through Tuesday. Sununu said he hopes
the governors will decide by their meeting this summer on what
strategies to pursue on regulatory reform, any changes in federal
laws and the possibility of a constitutional convention.
   The governors' list of 163 regulatory reforms includes a raft of
proposals for standardizing eligibility rules for food stamps and
Aid to Families with Dependent Children, and easing up on
strictures for running job training, education and health programs.
</TEXT>
