<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0768,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activists Released After Detentions, Solidarity Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To CORRECT punctuation, CLARIFY, SUB 11th graf, `Union
sources ... of Lublin.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Sunday began freeing
detained Solidarity activists who had been stopped from attending a
weekend meeting of the outlawed trade union.
   In southeastern Poland, meanwhile, eight farmers protesting
higher prices were arrested.
   Police in the provincial city of Rzeszow detained the farmers
during a march by 150 people chanting: ``We want meat. We want
bread.'' The march followed a national gathering of the banned
farmers' union, Rural Solidarity.
   Earlier at a Mass in Rzeszow attended by 2,000 people, local
Bishop Ignacy Tokarczuk sharply criticized the government's
treatment of peasant farmers.
   ``The countryside should be united and only then it will win its
demands,'' he said.
   The farmers' meeting coincided with the seventh anniversity of
the government's 1981 agreement to recognize Rural Solidarity as a
bargaining agent for farmers. The union later was declared illegal
following the imposition of martial law.
   On Sunday, authorities began to free members of the Solidarity
free trade union's national executive commission jailed over the
weekend just before a planned meeting called in Gdansk by
Solidarity chairman Lech Walesa.
   At least seven of the commission's 10 members and the union's
national spokesman, Janusz Onyszkiewicz, were taken into custody
Friday and Saturday.
   Opposition sources said a small group of Solidarity activists
managed to meet anyway, and that a statement would be issued later.
   Zbigniew Bujak, former underground chief of the union and the
Warsaw-region representative on the commission, was freed Sunday
morning from a downtown Warsaw police station, said Ludwika Wujec,
a Warsaw Solidarity activist.
   Union sources said others released later in the day were:
Onyszkiewicz, Wladyslaw Frasyniuk of Wroclaw, Antoni Stawikowski of
Torun, Antoni Tokarczuk of Bydgoszcz and Stanislaw Weglarz of
Lublin.
   There was no confirmation of the release of Stefan Jurczak,
representative for the Krakow region, and Bogdan Lis of Gdansk, but
they were also expected to be freed.
   In a sermon Sunday in Gdansk's St. Brygida's Church, the Rev.
Henryk Jankowski spoke angrily about the detentions.
   ``Man's right to freedom and his freedom of thought are
trampled,'' said Jankowski, an adviser to Walesa. ``This is an act
of lawlessness that does moral harm to the nation.''
</TEXT>
