<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APArts:1988Movies     02-21 0992</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: 1988 Movies,1013</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paramount and Disney Lead 1988 Movie Hits</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report. The name N!Xau in 12th graf, bgn,
`The Gods ..., is correct, as is Madolyn in 10th graf, bgn, Neil
Simon ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Pictures and the Disney Co. are
running neck and neck as the two giant film companies continue
their battle for box office supremacy.
   For the past two years, Paramount has been the unqualified
leader among major distributors, scoring with such blockbusters as
``Top Gun,'' ``Crocodile Dundee'' and ``Beverly Hills Cop II.''
   Paramount's share of the domestic film market was 20 percent in
1987, according to Daily Variety financial expert Art Murphy.
Runners-up were Buena Vista, the Disney distributing company, with
14 percent, and Warner Bros. with 13.
   In the first two weeks of 1988, Buena Vista took the lead on the
strength of the smash hits ``Three Men and a Baby'' and ``Good
Morning Vietnam'' _ 26 percent to Paramount's 17. It was a happy
triumph for Disney chairman Michael Eisner and Jeff Katzenberg,
Disney's film production chief; both had previously worked for
Paramount.
   But no matter who takes the box-office crown, everybody wins in
1988.
   ``Movie booms last at least 2{ years; the longest has been 3{,''
Murphy said. ``This boom has lasted a year and a half, and I see no
slowdown.''
   The year has opened strongly, with a record take of $100 million
in January. The period from Jan. 1 to Memorial Day is traditionally
the slowest period of the movie year, contributing 20 percent of
annual ticket stales, compared to 40 percent for the three summer
months.
   What wonders will theaters offer in the first five months of
1988? The mixture, as before, has a heavy accent on comedy.
   John Hughes invades the yuppie world with ``She's Having a
Baby,'' starring Kevin Bacon and Elizabeth McGovern. Ann-Margret
falls for her daughter's boyfriend, C. Thomas Howell, in ``A
Tiger's Tale.'' Joe Piscopo and Treat Williams play it for laughs
as cops in ``Dead Heat.''
   Neil Simon returns with the second of his autobiographical
trilogy, ``Biloxi Blues,'' with Matthew Broderick and directed by
Mike Nichols. George Roy Hill (``The Sting'') is back with ``Funny
Farm,'' in which New Yorkers Chevy Chase and Madolyn Smith try the
rural life. Richard Pryor as an engineer moves his family from New
Jersey to Idaho in ``Moving.''
   The ageless George Burns changes brains with his grandson in
``18 Again,'' which might bring to mind ``Like Father Like Son.''
   ``The Gods Must Be Crazy II'' follow the adventures of the
engaging African bushman, N!Xau. Richard Dreyfuss continues his
roll as an actor who impersonates a Central American dictator in
``Moon Over Parador.''
   ``Front Page'' is replayed in TV land with Kathleen Turner, Burt
Reynolds and Christopher Reeve in ``Switching Channels.'' Sally
Field and Tom Hanks star as a pair of stand-up comics in
``Punchline.''
   Those raucous rookies return in ``Police Academy 5: Assignment
Miami Beach,'' this time without Steve Gutenberg.
   Distributors always release a heavy load of dramas in the early
part of the year, when competition for the youth market is at a
minimum. The most anticipated film is ``The Unbearable Lightness of
Being,'' based on the modern classic novel by Milan Kundera. It is
the first movie by Philip Kaufman since ``The Right Stuff.''
   Also long-awaited is Robert Redford's first film as a director
since ``Ordinary People'' _ ``The Milangro Beanfield War,'' about a
New Mexico native who fights developers.
   After sinking with ``Pirates,'' Roman Polanski goes back to the
mystery-adventure genre with ``Frantic,'' starring Harrison Ford as
a surgeon whose wife disappears. Kelly McGillis and Jeff Daniels
appear in a postwar drama about the smuggling of Nazi criminals
into the United States, ``House on Carroll Street.'' Edward James
Olmos (``Miami Vice'') and Lou Diamond Phillips (``La Bamba'')
appear in ``Stand and Deliver,'' about a dedicated teacher in East
L.A.
   Roger Vadim has modernized his 1957 film ``And God Created
Women'' with Rebecca DeMornay in the role that helped make Brigitte
Bardot famous. Blake Edwards presents an imaginary teaming of Tom
Mix (Bruce Willis) and Wyatt Earp (James Garner) to solve a murder
mystery in ``Sunset.''
   Sidney Poitier returns to the screen as an FBI agent in a pair
of films: ``Shoot to Kill,'' a crime chase with Tom Beringer; and
``Little Nikita,'' with River Phoenix as son of Soviet spies.
   Alan Alda breaks his absence from films as director-writer-star
with Ann-Margret in ``A New Life,'' about a divorced pair seeking
new lives.
   In ``Bright Lights, Big City,'' Michael J. Fox abandons his
sunshiny image to play a cocaine-sniffing yuppie in the Manhattan
fast lane. Kelly McGillis and John Shea are pioneering Israelis in
``Dreamers.'' Don Johnson takes a shot at the big screen in ``Sweet
Hearts Dance,'' a romantic drama co-starring Susan Sarandon.
   The new year will bring plenty of action, too. Comic Jay Leno
makes his film debut as a Detroit cop teaming with a Tokyo
detective (Pat Morita) in ``Collision Course.'' Gene Hackman is a
pilot downed in Vietnam and Danny Glover is his rescuer in ``Bat
21.'' The Vietnam trend continues with ``Off Limits,'' in which
Willem Dafoe and Gregory Hines investigate murders of Vietnamese
prostitues.
   Academy Award winners William Hurt and Timothy Hutton combine
for a World War II thriller, ``Destiny.'' Sean Penn appears in two
films: ``Judgment in Berlin,'' as one of three East Berliners
escaping in an airplane; and in ``Colors'' as a police partner with
Robert Duvall battling Los Angeles gangs.
   The macho men are also back: Charles Bronson investigates Mormon
cult murders in ``Messenger of Death''; Scott Glenn is a cop who
becomes an Al Capone henchman in ``Verne Miller.''
   There's an ample supply of horror and teen films, as well as
some that are hard to classify: ``Eat the Rich,'' ``Killer Klowns
(from Outer Space),'' ``Hazing in Hell'' and ``Zombie Cop.''
</TEXT>
