<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Waldheim     02-21 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Waldheim,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Defector Says Waldheim Wasn't Working For Moscow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Austrian President Kurt Waldheim was never a
Soviet agent, according to his former under-secretary at the United
Nations, Arkady Shevchenko, a Soviet defector who lives in the
United States, a London newspaper reported Sunday.
   In light of allegations surrounding Waldheim's service in the
German army during World War II, there has been speculation in the
Western press that the Soviets might have held incriminating
documents against him and threatened to use them if he did not
comply with their policies when he was U.N. secretary-general from
1972 to 1982.
   The Sunday Telegraph said it was told by Shevchenko in
Washington recently that the speculation is unfounded.
   Shevchenko was reported as saying the Soviet foreign ministry
had other candidates in mind when Waldheim's name first came up for
the U.N. post.
   ``It was only when we saw he was likely to emerge as clear
favorite that we gave him our backing and actually put him up for
the job,'' Shevchenko said.
   Shevchenko defected from his U.N. post in 1978. Before taking
his post at the United Nations he was secretary in Moscow to Andrei
Gromyko, then Soviet foreign minister.
   The defector said he saw Gromyko's personal file on Waldheim.
   ``It mentioned that he had fought on our Russian front and had
been wounded there. But there was absolutely no reference to any
war crimes,'' Shevchenko was quoted as saying.
   Shevchenko was further quoted as saying that senior officials of
the Soviet KGB secret police in charge of Soviet citizens in New
York, complained of their inability to influence Waldheim in
getting more Soviets appointed to his staff and of their being
frozen out of his inner circle.
   An international commission has investigated allegations
Waldheim was involved in German atrocities in the Balkans in World
War II while serving in the German army. Waldheim has repeatedly
denied the allegations and has rejected calls that he step down as
president.
   The historians' commission, formed by the Austrian government,
concluded this month that Waldheim was ``in close proximity'' to
some Nazi atrocities in the Balkans, knew they were going on and
made no attempt to prevent them. It also said Waldheim concealed
his wartime past and tried to make it seem harmless once he could
no longer hide it.
   The commmission's report did not support allegations Waldheim
committed atrocities. But it left open the question of whether he
was guilty of any crime.
</TEXT>
