expected to return to work. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `The city...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Much of the city fire department's day
shift called in sick Saturday, apparently because of a dispute with
city officials over the equipping of new emergency units, a city
spokeswoman said.
   The city late Saturday afternoon persuaded Superior Court Judge
John E. Orton III to issue a temporary restraining order requiring
the firefighters to return to work Sunday, said Barbara Cottam,
spokeswoman for Mayor Joseph R. Paolino Jr. It is illegal for
municipal employees to strike in Rhode Island.
   Leo Miller, president of Providence Firefighters Local 799, said
he expected the firefighters to return to work Sunday. City
officials had vowed to return to Orton and seek contempt citations
if the job action continued, Ms. Cottam said.
   ``That's what the city tells you,'' was all Miller would say
when asked if the sickout was organized as part of a contract
dispute. ``What I'm going to say is that we thought we had a
contract with them but they have reneged.''
   Neither Ms. Cottam nor Miller had figures on the number of
firefighters who called in sick. The city covered the shifts of the
absent workers by holding the Friday night shift over, Ms. Cottam
said.
   The city, in a contract reached last year with the firefighters'
union, agreed to increase the number of rescue units in the
department from three to five.
   Ms. Cottam said the union is insisting that the two new units,
like the existing ones, be equipped with advanced life-support
equipment.
   ``That was never discussed or agreed to and it is not
necessary,'' Ms. Cottam said. ``The need is not there.''
   She also said the department does not have enough rescue workers
with the special training required for the advanced life-support
systems to staff five units.
