<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Shultz     02-21 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Shultz,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz, Shevardnadze Open Talks on Arms, Regional Conflicts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said his
government wants to play ``a more active role'' in the search for
an Arab-Israeli settlement as he opened talks Sunday with Secretary
of State George P. Shultz.
   The issue of Soviet participation is among key items on Shultz'
agenda for his two days of talks here.
   Shultz on Saturday said the Soviets should ``face up'' to their
human rights problems and establish relations with Israel if they
intend to take part in the talks he will try to set up when he goes
to the Middle East next week.
   But Shevardnadze, chatting with a reporter while waiting for
Shultz at the Soviet Foreign Ministry's elegant guest house in
central Moscow, said his government already was playing a
``constructive role'' in the region.
   ``We want to play a more active role also in the negotiations,''
he said.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir has resisted Soviet
participation in the search for a Middle East settlement.
   The Soviets have supported Jordan and Egypt in calling for an
international conference to serve as a framework for Arab-Israeli
negotiations. Shamir is cool to the idea, and appears to have
support from Shultz.
   Shultz' talks here are intended to prepare for the next
superpower summit meeting between President Reagan and Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev. It is to be held in Moscow, likely by
mid-summer, but the date has not been set.
   A date could be set before Shultz departs.
   Shultz flew in from Helsinki, Finland, where on Saturday he met
with reporters to discuss Soviet policy on human rights and
regional problems.
   The presence of Soviet troops in Afghanistan and U.S. support
for Afghan rebels is also on the agenda. Gorbachev announced
earlier this month that a Soviet pullout could begin May 15 and be
completed within 10 months if U.N.-sponsored negotiations in Geneva
next month can put together a formal agreement by March 15.
   Talks between Soviet and U.S. officials traditionally cover four
areas _ arms control, human rights, matters of bilateral interest
and regional conflicts.
