<2ND_LINE>BC-Pan Am-Strike, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0686,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pan Am, Teamsters Resume Talks As Strike Deadline Passes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE throughout with talks ending,
rescheduled for today, airline employees to go to work. Picks up
8th graf, `The 12:01...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks between representatives of Pan Am Corp.
and 4,500 Teamsters workers broke up Sunday after continuing six
hours past a 12:01 a.m. strike deadline, and union officials said
employees would return to work Sunday.
   The negotiations, aimed at resolving a dispute over Pan Am's
demands for wage cuts and work-rule changes, were scheduled to
resume Sunday afternoon, said Alex Calder, a spokesman for the
Teamsters' airlines division.
   Calder refused to discuss the status of the talks, saying the
union leadership is hesitant to read too much into them.
   Earlier Sunday, William Genoese, director of the airline
division of Teamsters Local 732, announced that the workers had
overwhelmingly authorized a strike, although he refused to release
figures on the vote.
   ``These people are fed up,'' he said of the workers. The
Teamsters union contends it has made sufficient concessions to aid
the financially ailing airline.
   Pan Am said that in case of a strike, it would maintain service
by using replacement workers for the union members, who are
employed as reservation clerks, customer service agents and in
various clerical positions.
   Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon said talks resumed at 10:30
p.m. Saturday in New York at the request of a federal mediator.
   Genoese said that despite the resumption of talks, there was a
good chance of a strike. ``They waited too long. They dragged their
feet,'' he said.
   The 12:01 a.m. deadline marked the end of a 30-day cooling-off
period mandated by the government.
   The Transport Workers Union voted Friday not to support a
Teamsters' strike, and the financially ailing airline's pilots,
flight attendants and flight engineers unions were not expected to
back a strike.
   Another Pan Am spokesman, Jeff Kriendler, said: ``The company is
prepared to negotiate and wants a settlement. But if there is a
strike we're fully prepared to operate.''
   Replacement workers, including management employees, were
trained and ready to replace strikers, Kriendler said.
   Genoese said Thursday that there was enough support for Local
732 among other Teamsters locals to cut off the airline's supplies
of fuel, laundry and liquor around the world.
   The union represents workers at airports in Boston, Detroit,
Chicago, Seattle, San Francisco, San Diego, Los Angeles, Hawaii,
Houston, Washington, New York and the Florida cities of Tampa,
Orlando and Miami.
   About 2,300 of the workers are employed in New York and another
1,300 are in Miami, Goenese said.
</TEXT>
