<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BostonHomeless     02-21 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boston Homeless,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey Finds Number of Homeless Up 17 Percent in Boston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of homeless people in Boston rose more
than 17 percent to about 3,400 in the last 15 months, and more
women and children are living on Boston's streets and in its
shelters than ever before, according to preliminary results of a
survey.
   Ann Maguire, director of Boston's Emergency Shelter Commission,
said the new figures were complied from a homeless census taken
early Friday, when more than 100 volunteers counted homeless people
in city streets and alleys.
   Boston officials said no other city in the country does similar
street counts. The first street census of the city's homeless,
conducted in November 1986, found about 2,900 homeless people.
   Of the approximately 3,400 counted Friday, 20.4 percent were
women, 10.5 percent children and adolescents and the rest men,
Maguire said Saturday.
   A survey of 26 cities released by the U.S. Conference of Mayors
in December found a 21 percent increase in the demand for emergency
shelter, ranging from a 44 percent jump in Kansas City to no change
in Louisville.
   The national survey found families with children accounting for
one third of homeless in 1987.
   Boston Mayor Raymond L. Flynn is chairman of the mayors
conference Task Force on Hunger and Homelessness. Boston increases
its number of shelter beds last year by 47 percent, Maguire said.
   In a telephone interview Saturday night, Flynn called on other
cities to conduct similar surveys to give the mayors conference a
weapon during congressional budget deliberations.
   Flynn said most members of Congress ``believe the problem is
basically confined to street people and don't realize the number of
families and mentally ill. We need the data to impress that upon
them.''
</TEXT>
