<HEAD>Tiny Sphinx Unearthed In Barain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sphinx small enough to fit in the palm
of a hand was found in the tomb of a woman who died 2,000 years
ago, one of a bounty of clues that may link two ancient
civilizations, experts said Sunday.
   The sphinx, only 1{ inches tall, was among 420 trinkets found
dangling from a necklace found at the burial site, which dates back
to 200 B.C. to 200 A.D., Abdel-Aziz Soweileh, Bahrain's antiquities
supervisor, was quoted as saying in the newspaper Akhbar Al-Khaleej.
   Also found was a scarab, a beetle-shaped insignia, and a perfume
vial. Analysis of a skeleton in the grave indicated it belonged to
a woman who was between the ages of 25 and 30 when she died.
   The newspaper quoted Soweileh as saying that the items may link
Bahrain's ancient Dilmun civilizations with Pharaonic Egypt. The
sphinx typically has the body of a lion and head of a man.
