<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs Injure 20 In Chittagong Marches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers hurled homemade bombs at
opposition party processions on the eve of a national holiday and
injured 20 people, police said Sunday.
   The injured included two policemen who were escorting the
marches in the port city of Chittagong around midnight Saturday.
   The attackers' identities were not known, police said when
contacted by telephone in Chittagong, 145 miles southeast of Dhaka.
   The marchers, from the Bangladesh Nationalist Party and the
pro-Moscow Communist Party of Bangladesh, were headed to the
Martyrs Monument to place wreaths as part of Sunday's nationwide
observance of Language Martyrs Day.
   The holiday commemorates the killing of six Dhaka University
students in 1952, when Bangladesh was part of Pakistan. The
students were shot to death by police during a demonstration
demanding that Bengali be made a state language.
   Bengali is the main language of Bangladesh, formerly called East
Pakistan. After the 1952 language campaign, Bengali was made an
official language of Pakisan, along with the Urdu of West Pakistan.
But the Urdu-speaking West continued to dominate the nation until
Bangladesh won independence in 1971.
   Language Martyrs Day was observed Sunday throughout Bangladesh,
including Dhaka, the capital, where opposition leaders Sheik Hasina
and Khaleda Zia placed wreaths at the Martyrs Monument outside
Dhaka University. There were no reports of trouble outside
Chittagong.
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad, a former army general who
writes poetry, planned to observe the day by reciting some of his
compositions to guests at his home.
   Hasina is leader of the Awami League and Mrs. Zia is head of the
Bangladesh Nationalist Party. Both women are spearheading a
3-month-old opposition campaign for Ershad's resignation.
   The protests frequently have turned violent as the opposition
presses ahead with strikes and rallies aimed at forcing Ershad to
vacate the presidency, which he assumed after leading a bloodless
coup in 1982.
