<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MercyKilling Bjt   02-21 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mercy Killing, Bjt,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AMA Journal Heads to Court over Anonymous Mercy Killing Article</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MENSING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the nation's leading medical journals is
headed for court in what may be its most serious editorial
controversy _ the publication of an anonymous article by a doctor
who described committing a mercy killing.
   The Cook County state's attorney's office wants the name of the
doctor, but the Journal of the American Medical Association, citing
a state free-press law, says it will be in court Monday seeking to
quash the subpoena.
   Letters to the journal have been about evenly split on whether
JAMA should have printed the anonymous essay.
   It's not the first time in recent years the 105-year-old
journal, the official publication of the country's largest
organization of physicians, has found itself in a clash over its
contents.
   In 1984, a U.S. Army medical expert charged that AMA officials
killed a story he had submitted on smoking so they could win favor
with politicians in tobacco-growing states.
   Two years earlier, the journal was accused of publishing an
article on heart medicine to placate a major drug company that was
an advertiser.
   JAMA officials denied the charges in both cases.
   The latest case involves the broader issues of press freedom and
mercy killing.
   In the Jan. 8 essay, titled, ``It's Over, Debbie,'' a doctor
described injecting a lethal dose of morphine into a woman dying of
ovarian cancer. He wrote that he did not know the patient, but was
asked to check on her and moved by her plea of ``Let's get this
over with.''
   AMA officials said they did not verify the incident but believed
it was based on fact. They said the author had requested anonymity.
The essay did not indicate where the doctor lived or where the
incident occurred.
   Last week, the Cook County state's attorney's office served JAMA
with a subpoena ordering it to name the writer of the article.
   AMA attorney Kirk Johnson said the journal would not comply.
JAMA officials said their attorneys would file a motion Monday to
dismiss the subpoena.
   The magazine's editors invoked the Illinois Reporters' Privilege
Act, saying it protected information obtained by reporters in the
course of their work. That means a judge must decide whether the
release of the author's identity is essential to the public
interest.
   Jane Kirtley, executive director of the Reporters' Committee for
Freedom of the Press, believes JAMA shouldn't have to release the
doctor's name.
   ``Even assuming a criminal activity occurred _ which I'm not
saying it did _ what possible justification does Illinois have to
say it occurred in their state? JAMA gets articles from all over
the country,'' said Ms. Kirtley, whose Washington-based group
provides legal and research assistance for journalists.
   JAMA, which has a circulation of 600,000 worldwide, including
365,000 in the United States, is one of the nation's most widely
read medical journals.
   Though it is generally considered less prestigious than the
Boston-based New England Journal of Medicine, it has ``a high
impact in clinical practice,'' said Dr. Eugene Garfield, president
of the Institute for Scientific Information, based in Philadelphia.
   Dr. George Lundberg, editor in chief of JAMA, said Friday he
received unanimous support from the AMA board on his decision to
run the article.
   ``We believe that the great issues of the day in medicine should
be debated primarily on the pages of JAMA,'' he said.
   Lundberg, 54, has sole authority to approve JAMA articles for
publication. When he became editor in 1982, he said he intended to
handle controversial issues more aggressively and make doctors more
aware of patients as people.
   JAMA has received 90 to 100 letters in response to the anonymous
article, according to a spokesman for the AMA, who refused to give
his name.
   While some of the letters have voiced opposition to euthanasia,
the rest have addressed whether JAMA should have published the
article _ and are evenly divided on whether the journal should have
published the article, the spokesman said.
   Dr. Edward J. Huth, editor of the Philadelphia-based Annals of
Internal Medicine, noted JAMA's willingness to take on
controversial issues such as AIDS and artificial hearts.
   However, he said, ``From my own point of view, we would never
publish an anonymous piece in a scholarly journal.''
</TEXT>
