<HEAD>Three Palestinians Killed; Leaflet Urges Resistance For Shultz
Visit</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with third death and army
confirmation, details and positive identifications. Picks up 8th
graf pvs, `A new ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot three Palestinians to
death Sunday in the West Bank, the army said, and clashes broke out
in towns and villages throughout the occupied territories.
   A military spokesman said two people were killed in the town of
Nablus, 40 miles north of Jerusalem, and another person was killed
in Ramallah, 10 miles north of Jerusalem.
   A doctor at Al-Ittihad hospital identified the Nablus victims as
Ramez Abu Amara, 18, who was shot in the heart, and Ahmed Saler Abu
Saler, 50, shot in the head.
   The doctor, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said 17 other
people were being treated at the hospital for gunshot wounds.
   The third victim was identified by hospital sources in Ramallah
and by the Arab-run Palestine Press Service as Kamal Mohammed
Fares, 24. They said he was shot in the chest during a
demonstration at the Deir Ammar refugee camp and died in the
emergency room.
   Hospital sources said two people were being treated for gunshot
wounds.
   According to U.N. figures, 62 Arabs have been killed since
unrest broke out Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. The figure
includes the death of a 12-year-old boy who died Saturday in the
Tulkarem refugee camp. The army is investigating the circumstances
of his death.
   A new leaflet was distributed throughout the occupied
territories, setting out a plan for Palestinian resistance to
coincide with this week's visit of Secretary of State George P.
Shultz.
   The leaflet, signed by the ``United National Leadership of the
Uprising,'' called for a series of strikes and demonstrations.
   ``Let us increase the occupation's political, moral and economic
losses and remember that the Vietnamese won their war against the
Americans not only with guns but also through the struggle of their
peasants,'' it said.
   In what has become a daily scenario, Arabs in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, seized by Israel during the 1967 Middle East war, threw
stones and bottles at soldiers, who retaliated with tear gas.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. aircraft carrier Coral Sea, along with the
Yorktown, a guided missile cruiser, and the destroyer Rickets,
dropped anchor in Haifa for what officials said was a regularly
scheduled visit, to last about a week.
   Asked if the visit was connected to Wednesday's kidnapping in
southern Lebanon of U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins, a U.N.
observer, Rear Adm. John K. Redy said no, but added the force would
be ready to take any action.
   ``I'm aware of what's going on in south Lebanon,'' he said.
``Our mission is not connected to that. I will not comment on
operational matters, but the mission of the Sixth Fleet is to be
ready to meet any contingency or any eventuality.''
   A clandestine pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem extremist group claims
to have abducted Higgins.
   Shultz is tentatively scheduled to arrive on Thursday for talks
on how to achieve a Middle East settlement.
   The leaflet's outline for ``national outrage in the face of the
Shultz visit'' calls for a day of solidarity Monday with those who
have died, been arrested or wounded in the unrest.
   A national hunger strike is set for Tuesday, general strikes for
Wednesday and Thursday, a day of demonstrations all over the
territories on Friday and a general defiance of curfews on Saturday.
   It was the eighth such leaflet published since the uprising
began.
</TEXT>
