<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Cardinal,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philippine Archbishop Rejects Anti-Communist Vigilantes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Aquino, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Jaime Sin said Sunday that
vigilante groups should concentrate on helping the poor and leave
the 19-year-old battle against communist rebels to the military.
   Sin, the Roman Catholic archbishop of Manila, said it also was
important to distinguish between rebels who espouse communism and
those who fight because they are poor and jobless with no hope of
lawful endeavors.
   Those rebels ``must be reintegrated again into society,'' he
said in a pastoral letter read in churchs throughout the capital.
   ``For those who take the gun, who espouse violence, who seek to
overthrow the government, who act without any regard for the value
of human life, the military authorities would be in the best
position to prescribe and implement the correct strategy,'' Sin
said.
   ``We in the church will be there to support the government's
counter-insurgency efforts,'' he said. ``It is our duty to be
peacemakers and we will do everything we can to promote peace.''
   Sin previously had expressed support for the military-backed
vigilante groups. But he said Sunday that when he made his earlier
remarks, ``I was expressing my approval of their concern for the
welfare and suffering of the poor.''
   The military maintains the vigilantes are needed to supplement
the armed forces. Critics charge the vigilantes are little more
than armed thugs who are guilty of widespread human rights
violations.
</TEXT>
