<DOCNO> AP880221-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-88 1144EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia-Kidnappings     02-21 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Kidnappings,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Members Of European Medical Team Abducted In Ethiopia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six medical relief workers from
Ireland, Belgium and the Netherlands were abducted by a rebel group
in the Ethiopian province of Tigre, officials said Sunday.
   Kidnapped were two nuns and a doctor from Ireland and two
Belgian doctors and a Dutch nurse affiliated with the international
aid group Medicins Sans Frontieres-Belgium, said Reginald Moreels,
a spokesman for the medical group.
   He said the six were kidnapped Thursday from their base in Idaga
Hamous, about 340 miles north of the capital of Addis Ababa, by
members of the rebel Popular Front for the Liberation of the Tigre.
   Moreels said the six apparently were unharmed.
   No reason for the abduction was immediately known, but Moreels
said fighting in the northern province had been intense over the
last few weeks and the rebels might have taken the doctors to treat
their wounded. Similar abductions to treat wounded have happened in
the past.
   Secessionist rebels in Tigre have fought the government of Lt.
Col. Mengistu Haile Mariam for several years.
   The two Belgian doctors were identified as Germaine Hanquet and
Michel Moreau and the Dutch nurse as Roland Raaijmaekers.
   The three Irishwomen were identified by the aid organization
Concern in Dublin as Dr. Anne Broderick, Sister Jacinta O'Sullivan
and Sister Bernadette Mangan. Both are from the Order of the Little
Sisters of the Assumption.
   The medical team was working on medical and nutritional projects
in Idaga Hamous, which has a population of about 3,000.
   Medicins Sans Frontieres, which means ``doctors without
borders,'' has sent medical personnel to crisis areas around the
world.
</TEXT>
