<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--FlorenceTraffic     02-21 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Florence Traffic,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Traffic Banned From Heart of City in Health Move</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLORENCE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traffic has been banned from most streets
in the heart of Florence in an attempt to save art treasures and
humans from harmful exhaust.
   The ban began Saturday, but its test will come with the start of
the work week Monday.
   From 7:30 a.m. to 7:30 p.m., only buses, taxis, residents and
commercial traffic making deliveries will be allowed in the center
of the city.
   All traffic was banned in some spots. They include the squares
in front of two of Florence's most famous churches: Santa Croce,
whose dark interior shelters the tombs of Michelangelo, Machiavelli
and Galileo; and Santa Maria Novella.
   Traffic Commissioner Graziano Cioni told reporters Saturday that
Florence's heavy traffic had been linked to an increase in lung
cancer. The exhaust also eats away at churches and Renaissance
palaces, forcing costly restoration and sometimes irreparable
damage.
</TEXT>
