<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-88 1149EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AmnestyAppeals     02-21 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty Appeals,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Immigration Service Trying All Kinds Of Things To Promote
Legalization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARLINGEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employing upbeat songs and down-home
block parties, federal immigration authorities are launching a
show-biz campaign to combat disappointing results from their
9-month-old alien amnesty program.
   With the May 4 deadline fast approaching, some critics say it's
all too late. Nevertheless, radio shows, a parade float, street
parties, bumper stickers and billboards are all part of the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service's package of ploys for
taking the message to eligible aliens.
   Art Zuniga, an INS official, even wrote a song _ ``Amnistia,''
Spanish for ``Amnesty.'' The INS has arranged for him to record it
this week and he will promote it at Spanish-language radio stations.
   ``It starts with, `Listen friends to the story I'm going to tell
you,''' Zuniga said. ``What comes to mind when I wrote this is that
in a sense it's a gift from this country to them.''
   The INS also plans to start putting fact sheets in tortilla
packages around the state, with the cooperation of several bakeries.
   Critics, though, wonder why the heavy promotion didn't start
sooner.
   ``I wish they'd done it a year ago when they needed to,'' said
Carter White, director of the American Civil Liberties Union's
South Texas Project based in San Juan. ``I think it's obviously
designed to counter the growing sentiment that they need to extend
the deadline.''
   Under the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986, most
eligible aliens were given one year, beginning last May 5, to apply
for legal U.S. residency if able to prove they have lived in this
country illegally since Jan. 1, 1982. Agricultural workers have
until Nov. 30 to apply.
   The INS had predicted about 2 million would apply for amnesty,
but as of last week the total was slightly more than 1.2 million
nationwide, according to the agency.
   In Texas, where up to 300,000 applicants were expected, 189,988
had applied by last week.
   Immigration officials are fighting a proposal in Congress that
would extend the deadline for a year.
   ``We've seen that the national campaign wasn't bringing in as
many people as we hoped it would, so we decided to start at the
grassroots level,'' said Virginia Kice, a former television news
reporter the INS hired last year to help promote the program in
South Texas. ``We need to try some more eye-catching things.''
   One of the latest promotional devices is a parade float the INS
built for the Washington's Birthday celebration in Laredo on
Saturday and other events in South Texas between now and the
deadline.
   The agency also has scheduled a series of live radio broadcasts
with Spanish-language stations at various legalization centers
around the state. Its most recent radio show, last Tuesday in
Arlington, drew a crowd of about 500, Ortiz said.
   Clara Escobedo de Martinez, at 98 the oldest to apply for
amnesty under the new law, has agreed to do a television commercial
for the INS.
   The agency also has rented billboards and lighted outdoor signs
and ordered bumper stickers bearing the bilingual slogan: ``Ahora
si, con Amnesty!'' (Amnesty Now!)
   On March 12, Boy Scouts will be distributing leaflets
door-to-door in the impoverished unincorporated rural areas of the
lower Rio Grande Valley known as ``colonias.'' At the same time, a
mobile sound truck will tour the colonias announcing the deadline.
   Carol Wolchok, director of the American Bar Association's
Immigration Law Implementation Project, said many eligible aliens
will not apply, either because they do not know about the program
or because they do not understand it.
   ``The publicity is important, and it should continue,'' she
said, ``but the program should be extended.''
</TEXT>
