<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Waldheim     02-21 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Waldheim,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>News Magazine Banned For Waldheim Swastika Cartoon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent news magazine was banned
temporarily because it printed a cartoon depicting President Kurt
Waldheim of Austria with a Nazi swastika over his mouth, according
to a published report.
   The biweekly Duga was back on the newsstands Friday after a
four-day ban that followed publication of the cartoon, the daily
Politika Ekspres reported. The magazine was banned before it was
distributed and new editions contained an advertisement in place of
the cartoon.
   The Belgrade public prosecutor slapped the temporary ban on the
magazine because the cartoon ``offended a foreign head of state,''
Politika Ekspres said in its Saturday editions. Offending a foreign
head of state is illegal in Yugoslavia.
   Politika Ekspres reported that the public prosecutor acted only
after ``getting a signal'' from Yugoslavia's foreign ministry.
   In 1948, Yugoslavia placed Waldheim on a list of suspected war
criminals and applied for his extradition, but never pursued the
request.
   Criticism about Waldheim's World War II conduct surfaced during
his 1986 campaign for president. A report by a commission of
historians said this month that Waldheim, a German army lieutenant
who served in the Balkans, was in close proximity to Nazi
atrocities, was in a position to know about them and did nothing to
prevent them.
   Waldheim has denied any wrongdoing. The lingering controversy
has led to calls from former supporters that he resign as president.
</TEXT>
