<DOCNO> AP880221-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-88 1202EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-All-MaleClubs Bjt   02-21 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-All-Male Clubs, Bjt,0709</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Time-Honored Clubs Challenged as Bastions of Bigotry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The future of the city's all-male clubs, the
prestigious gathering places for business and relaxation, is about
to be placed in the hands of the U.S. Supreme Court, until recently
a masculine sanctum itself.
   The high court will be asked Tuesday to decide whether the clubs
must admit women. Members say they are havens of tradition;
opponents say they are bastions of bigotry.
   ``For the old boys of the `Old Boys Network,' it is time to wake
up,'' said Marcella Maxwell, outgoing chairperson of the city's
Commission on Human Rights.
   Since 1986, the commission has charged four major clubs with
discriminating against women. The Union League Club and the New
York Athletic Club are awaiting hearings.
   The University Club has agreed to admit women. The Century
Association _ begun at a meeting of 19th-century intellectuals like
William Cullen Bryant and James Fenimore Cooper _ has said it will
comply if the Supreme Court upholds a local law requiring club
integration.
   At issue is a law which says clubs that have more than 400
members, serve meals and charge non-members who use their
facilities for business purposes cannot deny membership because of
sex, race, creed, color or national origin.
   The law was challenged by the New York State Club Association,
whose attorney, Alan Mansfield, refused to discuss the issue.
   In a Supreme Court brief, the city's corporation counsel says
the clubs in question ``provide entry into what is popularly known
as the Old Boy Network. The exclusion of women has greatly hampered
their ability to meet with other professionals and has limited the
opportunity for lateral mobility or upward advancement.''
   ``It is assumed that this is a very elitist and trivial issue
that only affects a very small number of women who have made it to
the top,'' said Lynn Hecht Schafran of the National Organization
for Women's Legal Defense and Education Fund.
   ``The fact is that people from middle management on up _ an
academic, a lawyer _ are constantly invited and instructed to
attend business functions at discriminatory clubs.''
   Two prominent all-women clubs, the Cosmopolitan and the Colony,
also might fall under the criteria of the law, said Schafran, but
the men's clubs are better known as settings for business deals.
   Schafran, who also is special counsel to the New York City
Commission on the Status of Women, guessed that about 25 clubs in
the city fall under the law's jurisdiction. Information on their
finances and membership would be needed to know for sure.
   To sidestep the law, a club could simply stop taking money from
non-members, said Schafran. Even so, women might be called upon to
do business with members there under embarrassing conditions.
   ``I have a legion of stories: women having to eat in a private
dining room while the men ate in the main dining room; being told
they can't walk on the stairs, can't come in the front door; there
are millions of variations on the theme,'' she said.
   Dan Perkes of Pelham, a member of the New York Athletic Club,
described it as ``a watering hole, a meeting place.'' Its grill is
open to men only.
   ``I've had business meetings there. If it involved a mixed
group, we took them to the 11th floor dining room. I've never seen
any overt fuss made of barring women,'' he said.
   ``The A.C. way is to keep a low profile,'' he added. ``As clubs
go, it's probably been far more liberal in its operations than
outfits like the University Club, those old-line luncheon clubs.''
   Women are banned from the Athletic Club's steam room and pool
because of male nudity. However, a pool at its Westchester County
facility is open to families.
   While the clubs also are banned from racial discrimination,
Sandler said the commission had received no formal complaints about
that type of bias.
   ``If a man belonged to club and invited a black colleague to
lunch and the colleague was told he couldn't sit in the lobby, the
place would go up in smoke,'' Schafran said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
