<2ND_LINE>AM-Senegal-Libya,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libyans Arrested Trying To Enter Senegal With Explosives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Libyans carrying arms and explosives
were arrested trying to enter Senegal at the Dakar airport,
Communications Minister Djibo Ka said Sunday.
   Ka, the government spokesman, told reporters the two Libyans
were arrested Friday night on their arrival on a flight from
Cotonou, Benin, via Abidjan, Ivory Coast.
   He said another man he described as a Libyan agent carrying
false papers had been arrested two days earlier at Kadira on the
Senegal-Mali border, where he was trying to enter Senegal by train.
   Ka provided no details on the arms and explosives that were
seized. He said the investigation was still in progress, and he
said more information would be disclosed later this week.
   Presidential and legislative elections are scheduled next Sunday
in Senegal, with President Abdel Diouf expected to win re-election
to a new five-year term.
   Senegal, a nation of 6 million people at the western tip of
Africa, has close ties to France and generally conservative,
pro-Western policies.
   It broke diplomatic relations with Libya in 1980, accusing the
regime of Col. Moammar Gadhafi of trying to destabilize Senegal and
other west African nations. Relations later improved, and Gadhafi
visited Dakar in December 1985, but formal ties have not been
resumed.
