<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     02-21 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPERVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Rathje says archaeology is
merely digging for ancient garbage, and he's updated the field of
study by sifting through America's trash.
   ``For me, the past is yesterday, not 1,000 years ago. Garbage is
our past and garbage is our future,'' Rathje, a professor of
archaeology at the University of Arizona, said in an interview
Thursday. ``It is a material artifact of our culture.''
   Information gathered from garbage helps reveal social trends and
landfill hazards and augments commercial market research, said
Rathje, who grew up not far from this western Chicago-area
community.
   He and his students have picked through landfills here, in
Tucson, Ariz., and in the San Francisco area.
   Two things his digs in Tucson documented were a sharp increase
in condom use and a rise in the number of people cutting fat off
meat since health warnings about fatty meat were first published.
   Although the diggings here have not been fully analyzed, they do
show things such as newspapers making up 15 percent of the garbage
by weight, compared to 9 percent in Arizona and just 4 percent in
San Francisco.
   The work is not always unpleasant. Rathje has found a diamond
ring and about $15 a year in coins.
   But then there was the time he took his student crew to lunch at
a crowded Tucson eatery after a morning of digging through a
landfill.
   Within a half hour, the other customers had cleared out and the
manager told him and his students when they left: ``Don't hurry
back.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The object was to build a machine
that could put a postage stamp on an envelope, and the entry from
Theta Tau fraternity won handily _ taking 33 steps and involving
dolls, eggs and a mousetrap.
   The not-so-simple contraption was an entry in the 1988 Rube
Goldberg Machine Contest held Saturday at Purdue University.
   The annual competition, named for the cartoonist who specialized
in drawing outlandishly complicated machines to perform simple
tasks, drew six student teams.
   The machines had to successfully complete the task in under five
minutes, using at least 25 steps, said Mike Barrett of Highland, a
student organizer.
   The Theta Tau machine's 33 steps included a miniature mailman
that braved rain, snow and an attacking dog; fluid that was forced
from a jar and into a tube spelling out ``David Letterman;'' a doll
of Indiana University basketball coach Bob Knight that was dunked
in a vat of green fluid; a sledge smashing an egg; a bubbling jar
of antacid, and marbles and a mouse trap.
   ``We started planning at the start of the semester, and spent
400-500 hours working on details of the project,'' said Steve
Zellers of Indianapolis, a senior in mechanical engineering and
spokesman for the winning team.
   For the device's grand finale, the envelope was shot into a
mailbox, which interrupted an electric eye and tripped circuits
that closed the mailbox door and flipped up a flag.
</TEXT>
