<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CampaignMoney     02-21 0866</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Money,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Tries Once Again to Limit Cost of Congressional Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats are trying once again to
resolve the biggest hangover issue from 1987 _ putting brakes on
the rising cost of congressional elections.
   Negotiations began last week with Republican opponents of the
Democratic campaign spending limit bill, which GOP senators were
able to derail last year with a gentlemanly filibuster.
   Headed by Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas, the
Republicans talked away 22 days of floor time and won a record
seven votes to end the debate, with the Democrats falling five
votes short of the 60 needed to win the so-called cloture vote.
   The legislation, with 52 of the 100 senators as co-sponsors,
made its 1988 reappearance on the floor last week, generating still
more debate amid talk of compromise and warnings from Senate
Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.
   Byrd, a principal supporter of the bill, said that unless
negotiators from both camps can work out a deal, he will get tough
and keep the Senate in session nights and weekends to break the
impasse.
   ``If there is going to be a filibuster this time, it is not
going to be a gentlemen's filibuster,'' Byrd said, referring to
last year's rather civilized daylight debate that never quite
reached the gloves-off stage.
   ``I don't want to see a filibuster, but if it comes to that I
suggest that senators cancel all evening engagements and be present
as long as the Senate is in session,'' he said. ``If it should
develop into a full-blown overtime filibuster, senators should
expect roll calls at any time.''
   Byrd's warnings were followed by both sides naming four members
each to attempt to negotiate differences in what Sen. Thad Cochran,
R-Miss., calls ``a power struggle between the two national parties
for control of the Senate.''
   Negotiators for the Democrats are Sens. David Boren of Okla.,
George Mitchell of Maine, Carl Levin of Michigan and James Exon of
Nebraska. The Republicans are Sens. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky,
Bob Packwood of Oregon, Ted Stevens of Alaska and Rudy Boschwitz of
Minnesota.
   They held their first meeting on Thursday without any tangible
result. An aide to one of the Democrats, speaking on condition of
anonymity, called it ``the Reykjavik of campaign finance reform,''
a reference to the unproductive U.S-Soviet summit of 1986.
   The negotiators are slated to meet again Monday, but the aide
said it appears one side or the other will have to make major
concessions to produce a compromise.
   The Democratic bill would set voluntary spending limits for
general elections to the Senate, ranging from $950,000 to $5.5
million, depending on a state's population. The average Senate
campaign cost $3 million in 1986, with the price soaring beyond $10
million in the big states.
   A candidate observing the limit would be able to get campaign
money from the Treasury if the opponent exceeded the limit or if an
independent group spent large amounts of money against the
candidate.
   Republicans argue that because they generally are more
successful in raising campaign funds, limits would hurt them more
than Democrats, especially as they continue to try to further their
gains in the South.
   The GOP critics also argue that the bill would further tilt the
playing field against them because it would do nothing about an
area where Democrats generally are ahead.
   This is the so-called ``soft money,'' the term used to describe
the aid given candidates by groups like labor unions, often in the
form of manpower for phone banks and door-to-door canvassing.
   Democrats so far have made no overt move to limit soft money,
arguing that even if they agreed to tighten up on this form of
campaign resources, the Republicans would still insist on no
spending limits.
   Democrats outnumber Republicans in the Senate 54-46. Two
Republicans are co-sponsoring the Democratic bill, Sens. Robert
Stafford of Vermont and John Chafee of Rhode Island. Sen. Nancy
Landon Kassebaum, R-Kan., was the third Republican supporting
cloture last year. Alabama Democrats Howell Heflin and Richard
Shelby voted against cloture.
   The Republican caucus has made opposition to the bill a
hard-line party issue. To win the battle, Byrd's forces will have
to break through the GOP ranks, picking up the votes of a handful
of Republicans who are said to favor spending limits but who thus
far have remained loyal to Dole.
   Last week the burner was turned up under four of them: Sens.
William Roth of Delaware, William Cohen of Maine, Arlen Specter of
Pennsylvania and Larry Pressler of South Dakota.
   They were the targets of full-page ads in newspapers back home
urging them to ``stop backing the filibuster that is protecting the
current corrupt campaign financing system.''
   The ads were purchased by Common Cause, the self-described
citizens lobby that is the most active organization pushing
Congress to change the campaign laws.
   The Senate is the main congressional battleground for campaign
finance legislation. The House has passed such bills in the past,
only to see them die in the Senate.
   House Democrats have drafted a campaign revision package for
House races but are sitting on it until the Senate approves
legislation.
</TEXT>
