<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PolioDrive     02-21 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polio Drive,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Of 1963 Polio Fund Distributed At Last</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY HELEN GILLESPIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOORESTOWN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $30,000 polio immunization fund
created in 1963 by the Burlington County Medical Society has
finally been spent, after one last round of donations.
   The last $1,000 recently was donated to a worldwide polio fund
sponsored by Rotary International, said Dr. Harold R. Reeve,
president of the medical society.
   Reeve, a urologist, said the final donation was ``a fitting
conclusion'' to the fund. ``There just wasn't enough to perpetuate
it anymore,'' he said in an interview last week.
   Before vaccines eradicated it in this country, polio was a
deadly killer and crippler of children and young adults.
   When the first oral polio vaccine became available in Burlington
County in 1963, the medical society arranged a mass immunization on
two Sundays in December of that year at schools and churches.
   The charge, if people could afford it, was 25 cents. Otherwise
the vaccine was free.
   About 100,000 people were vaccinated and the effort raised about
$70,000, with about $40,000 going to pay for expenses.
   The medical society decided the remaining $30,000 should be used
for the benefit of the community, Reeve said.
   Over the years the fund paid for first-aid classes, blood banks,
anti-smoking campaigns, a pollution study, physical fitness
programs and other public health projects. It was there when a
scabies outbreak closed one of the county hospitals and when county
officials decided to open a county health department.
   By the beginning of 1988, the fund had dwindled.
   ``It was down to nothing,'' Reeve said. ``I think a few people
had to chip in just to bring it up to $1,000.''
   He said the $1,000 donation will immunize 8,000 children against
polio in Third World countries.
   ``The people of this community had contributed to the welfare of
this community and now it is helping the world community,'' Reeve
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
