<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-88 1450EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ChildCare     02-21 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Care,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stronger Federal Role in Child Care Appears Inevitable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The difficult task of finding good and
affordable child care is drawing attention from so many diverse
groups this election year that a stronger federal role in the
patchwork system appears inevitable.
   Both liberals and conservatives are trumpeting the need to
address what some call a national crisis, spurred by the soaring
number of working mothers.
   And in the last two weeks, both the National Association of
Manufacturers and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce have cautiously
endorsed at least some form of federal involvement.
   ``The issue is certainly heating up,'' says Helen Blank,
director of child care for the Children's Defense Fund. ``We're
seeing more tragedies, more evidence of the system being fragile
because it's pushed too far. You push and you push and you push and
finally you start to fall over the edge.''
   The Children's Defense Fund was the moving force behind a $2.5
billion child care bill scheduled for hearings Thursday in the
House and the following Thursday in the Senate. Also under
discussion is a $375 million proposal sponsored by Republicans, who
have scheduled a news conference for Tuesday.
   The gulf between the two bills is wide, both in money and
philosophy. But proponents of the more ambitious plan say they are
heartened by the existence of the GOP bill, particularly because
its Senate sponsor _ Republican Orrin Hatch of Utah _ is among the
most conservative members of Congress.
   ``We have a tremendous amount of focus on child care and a
tremendous desire to do something. And when people want to do
something, there's usually room for agreement,'' Blank said.
   ``You always have an advantage in an election year,'' she added.
   The flurry of congressional activity follows several hearings
featuring the testimony not only of experts in child care and child
development but of people with first-hand exposure to the problem _
including a policewoman who found two children dead in a clothes
dryer. Their mother had tried and failed to find supervision for
them before she left for work.
   The $2.5 billion ``Act for Better Child Care Services,'' or ABC
bill, was introduced last year by Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,
and championed by the 122-member Alliance for Better Child Care.
   The money would be used to help states subsidize child care for
low- and moderate-income families, increase the number of child
care facilities and staff, and coordinate child care resources. The
bill also calls for federal health and safety standards for day
care centers and homes, and training standards for day care workers.
   The Hatch bill would give states $250 million for grants to
local governments, businesses and others to improve child care
services. The bill also would limit the liability of child care
providers, help states set up liability insurance pools, help home
providers make capital improvements and give tax credits to
employers with on-site child care.
   The National Association of Manufacturers last week adopted a
statement saying the federal government should ``encourage
affordable, quality child care through a bottom up approach and use
of incentives.'' The group said any legislation should allow
flexibility, address the liability problem and ``be guided by
fiscal realities.''
   The Chamber of Commerce board of directors, in a statement
approved Feb. 10, also endorsed a federal role providing incentives
and limiting liability. The government also should identify
programs and disseminate information, the chamber said, while
regulation should be carried out at the state or local level.
   ``All this points to a growing recognition that something has to
be done,'' Blank said of the Hatch bill and the two business
groups' statements. ``It just doesn't go far enough. ... We attack
the issue in a more systematic fashion. The private sector just
can't make day care on its own. We try to help the private sector
by creating a logical system in which they can invest.''
   Blank declined to discuss what kind of compromise might be
acceptable to the Children's Defense Fund except that it must do
more than the Hatch bill.
   ``It would be awful if we had some small child care bill that
didn't put us in the right direction,'' she said. ``It's very
important for the sake of children ... for us to really be cautious
and careful about what the federal government does after years of
inattention to child care.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880221-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-88 1448EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SugarBlitz     02-21 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sugar Blitz,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugar Industry's Ad Campaign Aimed At Sweetening Its Product's
Image</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn sugar and artificial
sweeteners are gaining a bigger share of the market, so the cane
and beet sugar industry plans to fight back with a $4 million
television advertising campaign.
   ``We'll associate sugar with happy moments,'' said Tony
Contreras, vice president of marketing for the Sugar Cane Growers
Cooperative in Belle Glade. ``It's a very positive, lifestyle-type
of campaign.''
   Following the lead of the beef, pork and poultry producers, the
sugar industry will try to increase consumption by focusing on the
``sweet, pure and natural'' aspects of sugar. The campaign starts
in March.
   Ads will be paid for by Florida's sugar cane growers and other
U.S. cane and beet growers, refiners and processors.
   ``The sugar market has dropped since the early 1970s. Actually
the market drop was caused by corn sweeteners,'' said Charlie
Shamel, president of The Sugar Association, a Washington, D.C.,
trade association.
   Manufacturers of soft drinks, canned fruit, table syrups and
other processed foods have turned to less expensive corn sweeteners
instead of cane or beet sugar.
   Meanwhile, total sugar consumption also is down. Per capita
sugar use could decline to 35 to 40 pounds by 1995 if the trend
continues, or less than half of what it was in the 1970s, Shamel
said.
   Unlike its magazing advertising last year which took a an
anti-aspartame tack, the Sugar Association TV drive will take a
pro-sugar approach. The campaign is geared toward giving viewers
``permission to eat sugar,'' Contreras said.
   ``We're not suggesting anyone pig out on sugar,'' said Shamel.
``But used in moderation, it tastes good and has a lot of benefits:
Adds texture in cakes, flavor to bland foods.''
   Past advertising by the sugar industry has been criticized for
its use of a U.S. Food and Drug Administration task force report
that the industry said confirms ``sugar is safe.''
   The 1986 FDA report found no direct link between sugar and major
diseases, such as diabetes, hypertension, cancer, gallstones,
glucose intolerances or hyperactivity in children.
   A Washington, D.C., consumer group claims the sugar industry
manipulated the FDA report.
   ``The study was part of a series of studies on food additives,''
said Bruce Silverglade, legal affairs director for the Center for
Science in the Public Interest. ``Sugar was thrown in there along
with artificial sweeteners. It did not focus on the role sugar
plays in the diet.''
   The American Dental Association maintains that while sugar may
be a natural product, ``it causes tooth decay,'' said Rick Asa,
spokesman in Chicago for the ADA, which favors sugar substitutes.
</TEXT>
