<DOCNO> AP880221-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-88 1506EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-ChenDuxiu     02-21 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Chen Duxiu,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Works of Purged Party Founder Published</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The collected writings of the Chinese Communist
Party's purged co-founder, Chen Duxiu, have been published for the
first time since 1922, an official report said Sunday.
   The publication, announced by the state-run Xinhua News Agency,
indicated that current party leaders are taking a more relaxed
attitude toward people who clashed with Mao Tse-tung during the
formative years of the Chinese Communist Party.
   Chen was the founder of the New Youth magazine that radicalized
many Chinese students in the 1910s and 1920s. He also was a leader
of the 1917 ``May Fourth Movement'' that opposed Japanese
expansionism and China's inability to fight it.
   He and Beijing University librarian Li Dazhao are regarded by
Western scholars as the Chinese Communist Party's founders. He
became the first party general secretary in 1921, but was ousted in
1927 after the failure of the party's policy of cooperating with
the non-Communist Nationalist Party of Chiang Kai-shek.
   Chen was strongly influenced by the Soviet-led Comintern, which
argued that China needed a democratic revolution before it could
proceed to a communist-style revolution.
   The Comintern, dominated by Soviet dictator Josef V. Stalin,
argued that China's middle class, represented by Chiang's
Nationalist party, would play a major role in the first revolution
and therefore deserved the help of all good communists.
   Chen supported that position and clashed with activists such as
Mao who believed that the party must split with the Nationalists,
establish its own roots among the workers and the peasants and work
directly for a communist revolution.
   Chen was purged from the party in 1929, partly at Mao's
instigation, and went down in Chinese history books as a ``right
opportunist,'' his role in the party's founding downplayed. He died
in 1942.
   Xinhua said the collection of 270 essays, letters and other
writings by Chen were republished by the People's Publishing House
in his native Anhui province in central China. It said the
collection first was published in Shanghai in 1922.
   Xinhua described the collection as ``invaluable to the study of
modern Chinese history and the history of the party in its early
stage.''
   During the last 12 years, Chinese authorities have moved away
from a blind allegiance to the ways and words of Mao, going so far
as to criticize his economic policies and blame him for the
excesses of the Cultural Revolution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
