<HEAD>Northern Ireland Police Chief Criticizes Inquiry Into His Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northern Ireland's police chief
charged Sunday that British investigator mishandled an inquiry into
allegations his force had a ``shoot-to-kill'' policy.
   ``John Stalker was considered to be the most proficient
detective investigator in the United Kingdom,'' Sir John Hermon
said of the former deputy chief constable of Manchester, who
investigated Hermon's force.
   But he said, ``I believe there are many people who are more
mature and more experienced who could have done it.''
   Hermon was speaking on a British Broadcasting Corp. Northern
Ireland television program to be broadcast Monday night. A partial
transcript of the program was released Sunday.
   Stalker was sent to Northern Ireland to investigate the killing
of six unarmed Roman Catholics by police in three incidents in late
1982.
   The British government announced Jan. 25 that while evidence had
been uncovered of a conspiracy to pervert the course of justice, it
would not prosecute any Northern Ireland police officers implicated
by Stalker. It said prosecutions would hurt national security.
   The decision has put a strain on Anglo-Irish relations. Ireland
views the case as a test of Britain's resolve to reform Northern
Ireland's justice system and protested the decision not to
prosecute.
   Stalker has published a book alleging that his investigation was
systematically obstructed by senior officers, including Hermon. He
claimed he was removed from the inquiry before he could complete it
because his findings were likely to lead to murder charges against
police officers.
   Five of the shooting victims were acknowledged Irish guerrillas
fighting to drive the British out of Northern Ireland. The sixth
was a Roman Catholic teen-ager with no connections to the
guerrillas.
   Their deaths in police ambushes led to allegations that
anti-terrorist officers were operating a ``shoot-to-kill policy''
to wipe out guerrillas without having to go through normal judicial
procedures.
   Hermon distributed a statement to police officers throughout
Northern Ireland last week accusing Stalker of publishing
``untruths, distortions, and inaccuracies.''
   Stalker, who has retired from the force, said he stood by his
book.
</TEXT>
