<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Socialists,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Launches Campaign Without Waiting For Mitterrand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEVERS, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just two months before the April 24
presidential election, the Socialist Party launched its campaign
Sunday under a large banner reading: ``Mitterrand Generation.''
   The only problem: President Francois Mitterrand has yet to
declare.
   Still, Mitterrand, who is a Socialist, is widely expected to run
for another seven-year term. The announcement will likely come in
mid-March.
   The official beginning of the Socialist campaign came before a
crowd of about 2,500 people in this city in central France, in a
region Mitterrand once represented in Parliament.
   Lionel Jospin, the party's first secretary, told the audience
that France was involved in ``an extraordinary campaign which we
are approaching in an unusual way, our candidate not being known,
the president being Socialist.''
   The slogan ``Mitterrand Generation'' has already appeared on
posters around France, which show a baby reaching up to the hand of
an unseen man. Party officials say the campaign could be adopted
either by Mitterrand as a candidate, or by his Socialist successor
if the president does not run.
   Opinion polls show Mitterrand in first place, with Premier
Jacques Chirac and former Premier Raymond Barre, both
conservatives, fighting for second place.
   The top two candidates in the April 24 voting will face off in a
decisive second round May 8, unless one of them wins more than 50
percent of the vote in the first round.
   In a radio interview Sunday, a leader of the Union for French
Democracy, an alliance of parties supporting Barre, said his side
was ``campaigning against a phantom who is hiding behind the
draperies at the Elysee,'' the presidential palace.
   ``Mr. Mitterrand would like to be a candidate without putting
his name on the ballot,'' said Jean-Claude Gaudin, president of the
union's parliamentary group. ``It's ideal for someone who does not
have many things to say and does have many things to hide.''
   Other candidates include Jean-Marie Le Pen of the extreme right
National Front, Andre Lajoinie of the Communists and Pierre Juquin,
a dissident Communist. All are running far behind Mitterrand, Barre
and Chirac.
   One paper seemed to have the answer Sunday.
   ``Mitterrand Has Made His Decision,'' was the banner headline in
the Journal du Dimanche newspaper. The story, however, said it did
not know which decision the president had made.
</TEXT>
