<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-21 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold In Northeast, Very Windy In Northern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Light snow fell only across parts of the Northeast on Sunday,
while high wind surged across the northern Plains.
   A large storm moving across central Canada generated strong wind
across northern sections of the nation east of the Rockies and was
expected to continue doing so for the next few days, especially
blasting the eastern slopes of the northern and central Rockies.
   Wind gusted to 68 mph at Havre, Mont., and caused some damage
Sunday morning, the National Weather Service said. Elsewhere in
Montana, gusts to 66 mph were reported at Livingston and to 56 mph
at Great Falls. In Wyoming, gusts were measured to 63 mph at Cody
and to 53 mph at Casper.
   The stiff wind stirred up snow already on the ground and blowing
snow cut visibility.
   A high wind watch was posted overnight and into Monday for
southeastern Wyoming and the foothills of northeastern Colorado.
   Scattered snow flurries fell from the eastern Great Lakes across
New York state to the mountains of northern New England, with some
accumulation in areas east of Lake Ontario.
   All of the Northeast was cold, with temperatures remaining below
freezing from the District of Columbia northward. Afternoon
temperatures were in the teens from eastern Ohio and most of
Pennsylvania across upstate New York to northern New England.
   Alpena, Mich., had a record low of 12 degrees below zero.
   Central and southern Florida turned cool and wet with
temperatures falling throughout the morning, into the 50s by
afternoon in southern Florida. Rain fell throughout much of the
peninsula during the morning but diminished by afternoon.
   The Pacific Northwest had patches of dense fog during the
morning and visibility at Portland, Ore., at 11 a.m. PST was down
to one-eighth of a mile.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 6
degrees above zero at Massena, N.Y., to 80 at Palm Springs, Calif.
The early-morning low for the day was 17 below zero at Gunnison,
Colo.
   For Monday, light snow or snow showers were forecast in northern
Maine and from western New York across northern Michigan, Minnesota
and North Dakota to Montana.
   Highs only in the teens or 20s were predicted in northern New
England; falling from the 30s to the 20s in most of Montana, North
Dakota and northern Minnesota; in the 30s from southern New England
to Pennsylvania and in the northern Great Lakes; in the 60s from
Florida to Mississippi; in the 60s or 70s from Louisiana to most of
Missouri and Kansas and from Oklahoma and northern Texas to much of
New Mexico, Arizona and California; in the 80s across the southern
half of Texas; and in the 40s or 50s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
