<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Death-Denied     02-21 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Death-Denied,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Find Body In Trailer, Relatives Say `God Dealing With
Him'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REFORM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities found a man's decomposed body at
a house occupied by children and other relatives, some of whom
claimed the deceased man was ``doing much better'' and would awaken
after his dealings with God.
   ``I understand they were seeing a voodoo man,'' Pickens County
Coroner Herbert Latham said of the deceased man and his relatives.
He said the man had been dead about three weeks when the body was
found.
   Pickens County Sheriff David Abston identified the dead man as
Jessie James Latham, 42, not related to the coroner. Abston said
Latham recently returned to Alabama from New York.
   L.C. Keasler, director of the Pickens County Department of Human
Resources, said agency workers went to the mobile home Feb. 14, but
were refused entrance. The agency workers returned Wednesday with
authorities and discovered the body.
   ``This was a weird case,'' the coroner said Sunday. He said that
when the body was located, the dead man's relatives ``tried to
convince me that he was still alive, that God was dealing with him,
that he was fine.''
   The coroner said the body ``was just dried up.'' He said an
autopsy was performed before the body was buried Saturday at a
local cemetery.
   The coroner said that although no foul play was suspected, he
was awaiting hospital records from New York before announcing the
cause of death. He said the deceased man was apparently aware he
was suffering from a fatal disease and was seeking help.
   The county workers had gone to the home in the first place
because an anonymous caller from New York had said he was sick and
that someone should see that he was taking his medication.
   Abston said that when Latham returned to Alabama from New York,
he was picked up at the Tuscaloosa Airport by his sister, Catherine
Latham, who took him to a motel in Reform. The two stayed there for
two weeks.
   Dilip Bhakta, the motel manager, said he never saw Latham, but
asked Latham's sister to leave the motel Feb. 2 ``because of the
smell.''
   ``She never would let anyone come in the room and would meet our
maids at the door to get materials,'' Bhakta said.
   Bhakta said the odor from the room ``was very strong _ very
offensive'' and that there were several complaints about it from
other guests.
   Ms. Latham said she took her brother on Jan. 22 to a man in Hale
County who advised that he drink goat milk with some pills he gave
him. She said she took her brother to the trailer residence on Feb.
2.
   The nine occupants of the trailer included two infants and
several teen-agers, the coroner said.
   Ms. Latham dismissed the claim that her brother was treated by a
``voodoo doctor.''
   Abston said the woman told him that her brother was alive when
he was moved and did not die until the day authorities found his
body in a bedroom of the trailer.
   ``He was pretty well decomposed at the time and the odor all
around the trailer was pretty strong,'' the sheriff said. ``Some of
the kids playing in the yard were wearing face masks, like in an
operating room.''
   Asked if there were any supernatural elements or voodoo involved
in the treatment, Ms. Latham told The Tuscaloosa News on Saturday:
``I don't like to use that word. I'm not working for the devil _ I
work for God.
   ``All I could do was minister to him. He's in God's hands now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
