<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz-Sakharov     02-21 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Sakharov,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Quizzes Sakharov on Arms, Human Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrei D. Sakharov told U.S. Secretary of State
George P. Shultz on Sunday the Soviet Union has not made enough
progress on human rights or Afghanistan to host a human rights
conference, but reforms are under way.
   Shultz visited the physicist and 1975 Nobel Peace Prize winner
at his seventh-floor apartment on a busy Moscow street to
underscore the Reagan administration's concern about the Soviet
human rights record.
   But Sakharov, who spoke to reporters for about 10 minutes after
the 55-minute meeting, said Shultz also questioned him about arms
control and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms.
   The Soviet Union wants to host an international conference on
human rights, but Western countries are resisting the idea because
of Soviet violations of human rights.
   ``As a precondition for such a conference, I see the liberation
of all prisoners of conscience, and the complete end of the war in
Afghanistan,'' said the 66-year-old Sakharov, who spoke to
reporters on the sidewalk outside his apartment building.
   Sakharov helped develop the Soviet hydrogen bomb in the 1950s
but increasingly turned his attention to human rights activities in
the 1960s and 1970s. He won the Nobel prize for that work, but was
exiled to the closed city of Gorky in January 1980 for speaking out
against the Soviet military intervention in Afghanistan in December
1979.
   Gorbachev said Feb. 8 that the Soviet Union could begin
withdrawing its soldiers from Afghanistan on May 15 if
U.N.-sponsored peace talks in Geneva are successful.
   Sakharov, dressed in a parka and fur hat, told reporters that
his first meeting with Shultz was a ``great honor'' and provided
him with valuable information. He excused himself after a short
statement, saying he had just recovered from the flu and could not
stay outdoors longer.
   Shultz visited the apartment with Assistant Secretary of State
Rozanne L. Ridgway, chief arms negotiator Max Kampelman, U.S.
Ambassador Jack Matlock and State Department spokesman Charles E.
Redman.
   A U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Sakharov's wife, Yelena Bonner, served tea to the group in
Sakharov's living room. Matlock served as translator, the official
said.
   Asked by reporters about the meeting as he stepped into his car,
Shultz said it was an ``inspiration.'' He then left for talks with
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze, whom he met earlier
in the day.
   Sakharov said Shultz asked him what the Soviet Union must do to
comply with the 1975 Helsinki agreement's provisions on human
rights. Sakharov said it was ``very important'' for the Soviet
Union to change legislation ``which makes punishment for one's
convictions possible.''
   On arms control, Sakharov said he reminded Shultz that he stood
for ``maximum restraint'' on the U.S. Strategic Defense Initiative,
or ``Star Wars'' program for a space-based shield against nuclear
attack.
   That issue is a stumbling block in talks that may lead to an
agreement to halve their arsensals of long-range nuclear weapons.
   He said he valued ``very highly'' the treaty eliminating
medium-and shorter-range nuclear missiles that Gorbachev and Reagan
signed in Washington Dec. 8.
   Sakharov told Shultz the Gorbachev's effort to restructure
Soviet society is a ``deep phenomenon'' and ``very serious,'' he
said.
   Sakharov has been less active in the dissident movement since
returning from exile in December 1986, but occasionally speaks out
on issues such as human rights, nuclear power and more openness in
Soviet history. He has returned to his work in the Soviet Academy
of Sciences.
</TEXT>
