<HEAD>U.N. Official Says New Urgency for Mideast Settlement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Goulding's arrival in
Cairo, scheduled meetings, details. Pickup 4th pvs: `Dudin said
...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE: Amman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior U.N. official said Sunday that
Palestinian unrest in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip has
created a new urgency for Arab-Israeli peace efforts.
   ``What has been going on in the occupied territories has created
a new situation,'' said U.N. Undersecretary-General Marrack
Goulding, who arrived in Cairo on the last leg of a regional tour.
   He told reporters in Amman, Jordan, earlier Sunday that the
protests, which began Dec. 8, underlined ``the pressing need for
progress towards an in-depth negiation for a just and lasting
settlement.
   ``And I think it has brought home to all concerned that everyone
has got to make a major effort,'' he added.
   Goulding's two-day visit in Egypt is his last stop on a tour
that took him to Tunisia, Lebanon, Syria and Jordan. He visited
Israel last month.
   The U.N. envoy was scheduled to meet with Foreign Minister Esmat
Abdel-Meguid for talks on regional developments, Egypt's state-run
Middle East News Agency said.
   The official Jordanian News Agency said that Marwan Dudin,
acting foreign minister of the occupied territories, told Goulding
in Amman earlier in the day that Israeli forces had killed 108
Palestinians in the unrest, far more than the 61 deaths reported by
the United Nations.
   Dudin said Israeli forces had injured more than 3,000 Arabs.
   ``Mr. Dudin gave me a list of names and ages, locations and
dates, which I haven't had a chance to look at yet,'' Goulding
said. ``But we won't be carrying out a U.N. investigation as such.''
   Dudin's ministry is in charge of Jordanian affairs in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel captured from Egypt and Jordan in
the 1967 Middle East war.
   Most of the estimated 900,000 Arabs on the West Bank and some of
the 600,000 in the Gaza Strip are citizens of Jordan.
   Goulding's visit comes a few days before U.S. Secretary of State
George P. Shultz is scheduled to arrive in Israel. Shultz is
expected to discuss recent U.S. suggestions to grant limited
self-government to Palestinians in the occupied territories as a
step toward a final Arab-Israeli peace settlement.
   ``In some places, I encountered a sense of satisfaction that the
United States is becoming active again on this issue, and there is
obviously great interest in what Secretary Shultz is going to
say,'' Goulding said.
   But he added, ``I cannot claim to have encountered a great deal
of optimism.''
</TEXT>
