<HEAD>NYC Mayor Koch Ends $7 Movie Ticket Boycott</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch says he is giving up his
campaign to boycott Manhattan movie theaters that charge $7
admission because moviegoers weren't going along.
   ``It's clear to me that moviegoers distressed with the higher
prices are nevertheless willing to pay them, having no alternative
other than to boycott, which they have not been doing,'' the mayor
said Sunday through his spokesman, Lee Jones. ``Boycotts without
mass support don't prevail.''
   The mayor's 46-day boycott targeted 44 theaters that had raised
admission prices from $6 to $7.
   Koch says that next weekend he'll probably see his first $7
movie since the boycott began, Jones said.
   Joanne Zyontz, leader of a group calling itself Boycott $7, said
her organization will continue its effort.
   ``We were happy to have the mayor's voice in our fight but we
will not drop the battle at this point,'' Ms. Zyontz said. ``If we
ignore the $7 ticket, next year it will be $10.''
