<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-88 1925EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-NearCollision     02-21 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Near Collision,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Pan Am, British Caledonian Planes in Near Collision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pan American jet and a British Caledonian
aircraft, carrying a total of 222 people, nearly collided over the
southeast coast of England on Sunday, the British airline said.
   An air traffic controller was later suspended _ standard
procedure according to the Civil Aviation Authority, which said the
incident is under investigation.
   It is the second near-collision in southern England in two weeks
and the latest in a series of incidents this year that have raised
concern about safety among the controllers.
   British Caledonian said its BA 1-11, carrying 70 people, was
about 25 minutes out of London's Gatwick airport bound for
Amsterdam when its pilot saw the Pan Am Boeing 727 on ``a
converging course'' just below and slightly less than one mile
away, near Southend, Essex at 9 a.m.
   The American airliner with 152 people aboard was headed for
London's Heathrow airport from Oslo, Norway.
   ``As far as the B-Cal captain is concerned, he did not have to
make any alteration to course and had the other plane in sight at
all times,'' said a British airline spokesman, unidentified in
keeping with British practice.
   ``He noticed that although there was a potential conflict, the
Pan-Am aircraft changed its heading,'' the spokesman said.
   Press Association, the British domestic news agency, said the
American plane altered its course on instructions from air traffic
control after a potential disaster was realized.
   British Caledonian said its pilot filed an ``air miss'' report
and that the Pan Am pilot was also filing a report.
   Aviation authority officials said they did not know exactly how
far apart the two planes were.
   Aircraft are supposed to be three miles apart horizontally and
1,000 feet vertically.
   One air traffic official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said it appeared the incident happened when one of the two planes
descended below its cleared altitude.
   ``We are not sure at this stage which one,'' the official said.
   An aviation authority spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping
with British practice, said: ``Our preliminary findings indicate
that it was not a serious air miss, but it's difficult to say what
the separation was at the moment.''
   He said controllers were suspended until an investigation has
``ruled out any gross error by air traffic control.''
   Two weeks ago a British Airways Lockheed L1011 and a Balkan
Bulgarian Tu-54 with a total of about 500 people on board were
involved in a near-collision over the Kent coast.
   Two air traffic controllers were suspended and Transport
Secretary Paul Channon ordered a special inquiry into the
circumstances of that incident.
</TEXT>
