<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-88 1931EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Peres-Pipeline     02-21 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peres-Pipeline,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres Says He Wrote To Meese About Proposed Iraqi Pipeline Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres
acknowledged Sunday that he wrote to Attorney General Edwin Meese
III in 1985 about a proposed Iraqi pipeline, but said the note only
indicated that he wanted to discuss the matter with Secretary of
State George Shultz.
   Peres, who was Israel's prime minister at the time, previously
has denied writing to Meese that he supported the $1 billion,
540-mile pipeline project, which was never built.
   Appearing Sunday on ABC-TV's ``This Week With David Brinkley,''
Peres said he had sent Meese a handwritten note regarding the
project during the summer of 1985.
   ``I was told about the idea of laying a pipeline from Iraq
through Jordan up to Elat, which will add, in my judgment, more
security to the whole region and that Israel could have enjoyed oil
for a lesser price,'' Peres said.
   ``Once I was told, I wrote to Meese and I said that if this is
the case, I would like to meet Secretary Shultz, a man for whom I
have the highest regard, in order to discuss it and talk it over.
That was the content of my letter,'' he said.
   Peres has said Meese sent him a handwritten letter in which the
attorney general directed him to deal with then-National Security
Adviser Robert McFarlane instead of Shultz.
   The Los Angeles Times reported earlier this month that Meese
told Peres to bypass Shultz because of a potential conflict of
interest. Shultz used to be an executive with Bechtel Corp., the
huge San Francisco construction firm which had submitted a bid to
build the pipeline.
   Independent counsel James McKay, who is conducting a criminal
probe of Meese, is investigating the attorney general's role in the
pipeline project.
   Meese has said his involvement in the project was ``entirely
lawful, proper and responsible.''
   At issue in particular is a 1985 memo sent by attorney E. Robert
Wallach to Meese describing the proposed project and mentioning
planned payoffs to the government of Israel and Peres' Labor Party
to ensure that Israel would not attack the pipeline.
   Wallach, a longtime friend of Meese, had been hired by Swiss
businessman Bruce Rappaport, who had been enlisted by Bechtel to
help with the project due to his close ties to Israeli government
officials.
   Federal law prohibits U.S. citizens from bribing foreign
officials and states that the attorney general may take legal
action to stop a violation if it appears that one is about to occur.
   Rappaport has said he did not intend to pay bribes and that the
payments would be standard business procedure and would come from
profits from the pipeline or discounts on the oil.
   Peres has denied repeatedly that anything of value was offered
or accepted by him or his Labor Party in connection with the
pipeline. He repeated that denial Sunday.
   Meese has said that he doesn't recall reading the portion of the
memo mentioning payments, but said, ``I do not believe that it
fairly implies that a violation of law was committed or
contemplated in connection with the pipeline.''
</TEXT>
