<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-MineBlast 1stLd-Writethru   02-21 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Mine Blast, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0702,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mine Explodes in English Channel; Crew Rescued After Boat Sinks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with authorities saying mine
apparently from World War II. Pulled up in boat's nets. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHERBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mine apparently left over from World
War II sank a French trawler in the English Channel on Sunday when
it exploded in the boat's fishing nets, but all four crew members
were rescued safely, officials said.
   An official at the CROSS-MA search and rescue headquarters in
Cherbourg, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the boat La
Minette hit the mine early Sunday morning about 30 miles north of
the Normandy coast.
   A nearby trawler rescued the crew members and brought them back
to Port-a-Bessin, their home port, 25 miles northwest of Caen.
   Another official at CROSS-MA said authorities believed the mine
was one of many remaining after the June 6, 1944 Allied assault on
German defenses in Normandy.
   The official, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, said
fishing boats drag up World War II-vintage mines or shells about
once a month, but explosions are rare.
</TEXT>
