<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-US     02-21 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-US,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Recounts Marcos's Departure</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Aquino, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino recalled
Sunday that when Ferdinand Marcos was preparing to go into exile,
she reluctantly allowed him to stay overnight at U.S.-run Clark Air
Base.
   But Mrs. Aquino said on her weekly radio show that she had
refused to let the ousted president go to his home province.
   Mrs. Aquino also said she had been told of the coup plot against
Marcos that led to the ``People Power'' revolution Feb. 22-25 1986
but she did not believe the planners would go through with it.
   Mrs. Aquino said Sunday night that the role of the U.S. Embassy
during Marcos' final hours as president was ``making arrangements
for Marcos to leave the country.''
   Marcos has claimed he was kidnapped by U.S. authorities and
tricked into boarding a plane, thinking he would be flown to Ilocos
Norte, his home province in the northern Philippines.
   But Mrs. Aquino said U.S. Ambassador Stephen Bosworth called her
the evening of Feb. 25 to say the Marcoses would be flown to Clark.
   After the Marcoses reached the base, Bosworth called her again
and asked if they could stay overnight at the base and then fly to
Ilocos Norte for a rest, she said.
   ``I said no, he can rest in Clark, but he has to leave first
thing in the morning. And so that was the agreement, and that was
why Marcos and his family flew the next day to Honolulu,'' she said.
   Mrs. Aquino invited listeners to join a ``Chain for Peace''
during second anniversary celebrations Thursday along a road
dividing the two military camps where the revolt occurred.
</TEXT>
