<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Parole-NewbornDeath     02-21 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Parole-Newborn Death,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Convicted In Newborn's Death Is Granted Parole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLATTE CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman convicted of involuntary
manslaughter in the death of her baby on an airliner has been
paroled after serving 120 days of a five-year sentence.
   Julie Killeen, 22, of San Francisco pleaded guilty in October
and was sentenced by Platte County Circuit Judge John Yeaman.
   Yeaman placed Ms. Killeen on probation earlier this month, but
declined to say why. California authorities will supervise her
probation.
   Ms. Killeen's daughter was born June 30 in the lavatory of a
Miami-bound airliner during a 45-minute layover at Kansas City
International Airport, authorities said. The baby died of
suffocation.
   Ms. Killeen told police she dumped the baby's body in a trash
can after the plane arrived at Miami International Airport so that
her father wouldn't know she was pregnant. She also said she
thought the baby was stillborn.
   A maintenance worker found the infant girl's body in the Miami
airport trash can.
</TEXT>
