<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Ortega     02-21 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Ortega,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan President Says Non-Lethal Aid To Contras Means More War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the U.S. Congress approves new
non-lethal aid for the Contra rebels it will be ``erasing the word
peace,'' President Daniel Ortega said Sunday.
   In a two-hour speech at the opening session of the National
Assembly, Ortega said the United States ``continues to propitiate
and finance the war against Nicaragua and despite the vote of
Congress against that aid, this chapter has not closed.''
   He said President Reagan will look for a way to obtain more
financing for the Contras by calling the assistance humanitarian
aid.
   ``If the North American Congress approves that type of
financing, it would be erasing the word peace that it wrote when it
voted against the funds, and would be putting (in) the word `war,'
'' he said in the speech, broadcast over a government national
radio network.
   ``That is the little game of Congress, a Congress where many
interests, particularly egotistical, are involved and which is
playing with life, hunger, security and the self-determination of
the Nicaraguan people,'' he said.
   Reagan lost his bid in a House vote Feb. 3 for a $36.2 million
aid package that included about $3.6 million for weapons and
ammunition, along with additional millions for military logistical
support for the rebels fighting the leftist Sandinista government.
   Democrats prevailed in that vote, 219-211, after the party's
leadership promised wavering members that there would be a later
opportunity to vote on a package of Contra aid that included only
food, clothing, medicine and shelter.
   A group of Democrats, together with one or two Republicans who
voted against the president's proposal, have been meeting to draft
such an alternative.
   Ortega claimed in his speech that the U.S. Embassy in Managua is
financing opposition groups ``including the Communist Party.''
   Deputies from the Communist Party and two other opposition
parties did not attend the assembly session.
   Among the invited guests were Uruguayan Vice President Enrique
Ernesto Tarigo Vasquez and the Rev. Roy Bourgeois. The Roman
Catholic priest was sentenced to 10 months in jail for trespassing
during a demonstration at an Air Force base in Florida where
Nicaraguan rebels reportedly were being trained.
   In the speech, Ortega said 26,500 people have been killed since
the war began in 1981 and 23,882 others wounded. Other sources have
said unofficially in the past that more than 40,000 have died.
   The war, he said, has cost the country $3.6 billion.
   In 1987 alone, he said, damage to the economy from the war
totaled $376 million, more than the country's exports of $270
million.
   Despite the war, he said, the economy expanded at an
inflation-adjusted rate of 1.7 percent. It contracted 0.4 percent
in 1986.
   Ortega said consumer prices soared a whopping 1,347 percent last
year, compared to 657 percent in 1986.
   The government recently unveiled a new program to try to control
the runaway inflation rate, introducing a new cordoba currency,
boosting prices of basic goods, increasing salaries and cracking
down on speculators.
   Ortega also praised the strategic weapons agreement between the
United States and the Soviet Union.
   ``Those agreements tell us that if understanding is possible at
those levels, it may be easier for there to be understanding at
other levels, and particularly in places where there are conflicts
as in Nicaragua,'' he said.
</TEXT>
