<HEAD>South Korea Plans Early Repayment of World Bank Loans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will repay $500 million
in loans from the World Bank ahead of schedule, the Finance
Ministry said Monday.
   Officials said the ministry plans to pay back the loans within
the first half of this year, but has not set an exact date.
   The ministry officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the decision was in response to the bank's request for an
early partial repayment. South Korea now owes the bank $3 billion
in loans.
   Buoyed by strong exports amd a surging current account surplus,
South Korea repaid about $9 billion in public and commercial loans
last year, reducing its total debts to $35.6 billion by the end of
the year.
   South Korea's current account surplus in 1987 more than doubled
to $9.78 billion from $4.61 billion a year ago.
   Current accounts measure trade in merchandise and services plus
some other international transactions.
</TEXT>
