<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kenya-Elections     02-21 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Elections,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kenya Tests Controversial Ballot For Party Nominations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the ruling Kenya African
National Union party test a controversial ballot-by-queueing system
Monday when, for the first time, they nominate candidates for
general elections.
   Under the new system, which the party introduced in 1986 to stop
corruption and give members a bigger voice, they will nominate an
estimated 750 candidates to contest March 21 general elections for
Parliament.
   Thousands of other candidates are standing for seats on urban,
rural and district councils.
   In previous elections, scheduled every five years, candidates
were nominated by three people _ the party chairman,
secretary-general and treasurer. President Daniel arap Moi also is
president of KANU.
   By law, Kenya is a one-party state and KANU must approve all
candidates. Some 4.3 million of the 20 million people are party
members eligible to queue during Monday's nominations.
   The secret ballot will be used at the general elections, in
which all citizens aged over 18 years and registered to vote can
take part. There are 5.5 million registered voters.
   Some voters will not have the opportunity. Candidates who win
more than 70 percent of votes at Monday's party nominations
automatically go to the 200-member Parliament.
   Church leaders, lawyers and a few politicians have criticized
the regulation and the new system, where voters must stand in a
line behind their candidate.
   Results of Monday's nominations will be published at the end of
February, when the party also is holding presidential nominations.
But nobody is expected to challenge Moi, who has ruled Kenya for 10
years since the death of its first president, Jomo Kenyatta.
   The nation became independent from Britain 25 years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
