<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AIBankruptcy Bjt   02-21 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AI Bankruptcy, Bjt,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allegheny International Files for Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Allegheny International Inc.
insists the consumer products company will continue business as
usual even though it has filed for reorganization under federal
bankruptcy laws.
   The Pittsburgh-based company and some of its subsidiaries filed
for Chapter 11 reorganization in U.S. Bankruptcy Court on Saturday.
   The company has total debts of around $845 million, while its
assets are estimated at $735 million.
   ``I'm confident AI will emerge a stronger and more viable
company,'' Allegheny International Chairman Oliver S. Travers said
in a statement.
   Included in the filing for reorganization and protection from
creditors are Allegheny International; Sunbeam Corp., its principal
subsidiary; Almet-Lawnlite Inc., Sunbeam's subsidiary; Sunbeam
Holdings Inc.; and Chemetron Corp.
   Allegheny International said a $175 million line of credit has
been arranged through two major New York banks.
   The credit line, the company said, provides enough cash to run
the companies during the reorganization.
   ``The reorganization will enable AI to operate with the
stability needed to continue the successful growth of its consumer
products operations and improve its complex capital structure,''
Travers said.
   ``Chapter 11 provides the means to implement corporate
restructuring and continue the company's profitable turnaround,''
said Travers, chairman since 1986.
   The action provides court authorization for the company to
continue normal operations, he said. ``It's business as usual at
our facilities.''
   Travers said Allegheny International sought court protection
because its complex capital structure and excessive debt could not
be refinanced and reorganized without court protection.
   Sunbeam and Almet-Lawlite are profitable, Travers said, and
wouldn't have had to file for protection if it weren't for
Allegheny International's complex financial situation.
   Consumer products manufactured by Sunbeam include small
household appliances, electric blankets and barbecue grills.
Almet-Lawnlite makes lawn and patio furniture.
   The bankruptcy filing does not affect Sunbeam Corp.'s consumer
products operations in Canada, Mexico, Venezuela and Peru,
according to the company. It also does not affect industrial and
high-technology companies that Allegheny International is in the
process of divesting.
   Since a change in Allegheny International's management in August
1986, the company said it has sold 19 subsidiaries. The company
said it also has reduced expenses and focused on its consumer
products operations.
   Last September, the Securities and Exchange Commission charged
the company with failing to record and to disclose perks given to
former chairman Robert J. Buckley and other executives, including
the use of company-owned residences and aircraft.
   Allegheny International, prior to 1981, was known as Allegheny
Ludlum Industries. The company acquired Sunbeam Corp. that year for
$534 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
