<DOCNO> AP880221-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-88 1911EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Ford'sMoney-Watcher     02-21 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford's Money-Watcher,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>It's Not Easy Watching All That Ford Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When you're in charge of handling $7 billion in
cash, sometimes a million or two can slip through the cracks, says
Ford Motor Co. money-manager Malcolm S. Macdonald.
   Macdonald, assistant treasurer for the world's No. 2 automaker,
says he flew into a panic once when $5 million couldn't be
accounted for.
   The trouble began when he asked a bank to send $5 million to the
Central Bank of Brazil. The bank sent the money to the Central Bank
of Bolivia instead.
   ``There was a period of time when I was concerned about my
career prospects,'' he said.
   Keeping track of the growing nest egg of one of the nation's
most profitable corporations can lead to a lot of anxiety,
Macdonald acknowledged.
   ``I wake up in the middle of the night sweating,'' he said.
   Macdonald watches over more than $7 billion of Ford's $10
billion-plus in cash and marketable securities.
   The money he watches is the money Ford keeps on hand to pay its
workers and its bills and to finance acquisitions. The rest of
Ford's liquid assets are handled by Ford of Europe.
   Ford, which earned an automotive industry record $4.6 billion in
1987, entrusts more than 20 percent of its total assets to
Macdonald, who invests cash while making sure there's enough on
hand to pay operating expenses.
   Macdonald and his 26-person staff have to be careful how they
invest the money, because the automaker must be able to get to it
at all times.
   ``All our investments must be liquid. If Mr. (Bruce) Blythe
calls us up one day and says `I need $1 billion on March 30 to
complete an acquisition,' we can't say `Gee, that's going to be
kind of tough. We bought these bonds, and we can't sell them
yet,''' Macdonald said.
   Blythe directs Ford's diversification planning.
   The guidelines that Macdonald and his staff follow in investing
Ford's cash allow them to buy only high-grade securities and
prohibit them from playing the stock market.
   ``On Oct. 19 we were very grateful for that policy. There is
plenty of risk in the car business without trying to get rich in
the securities business,'' Macdonald said.
   Ford tries to keep less than $10 million in its bank accounts
overnight because banks pay limited interest on corporate checking
accounts, he said. The biggest chunk of Ford's money goes into U.S.
Treasury bills and other government and corporate bonds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880221-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-88 2017EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PanAm-Strike 3rdLd-Writethru f0041 02-21 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pan Am-Strike, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0041,0673</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to add Pan Am threat to discipline workers
involved in `warfare.' INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th graf pvs, `There's
going...', with further comment from spokesman, picking up 7th
graf, `Negotiations began...'; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks between Pan Am Corp. and the 4,500-member
union representing reservation clerks broke off Sunday. The union
vowed to disrupt operations through ``guerrilla warfare'' but put
off any strike.
   Pan Am officials said airline service continued without
interruption even if there eventually is a walkout, and threatened
to discipline any workers disrupting service. But the federal
mediator involved in the negotiations said he was optimistic the
two sides would return to the bargaining table.
   ``We can strike any time we want,'' said William Genoese,
director of the Teamsters airline division. ``We're going to pick
our strategic time.''
   Asked when that might be, Genoese said, ``Today, tomorrow, next
week, next month ... When it hurts them the most.'' The union had
originally set a strike deadline for 12:01 a.m. Sunday.
   Genoese said reservation clerks and other Teamsters members
would attempt to disrupt Pan Am operations through ``guerrilla
warfare,'' starting immediately.
   ``There's going to be trouble on the job,'' he said. ``They're
not going to correct anybody's errors, they're not going to help
anybody, they're not going to do anything for anybody. ... There's
no more talks as far as we're concerned. We are at war with them,
complete warfare.''
   But a Pan Am spokesman, Jeff Kriendler, called Genoese ``the
jerk'' and his threat ``completely ridiculous.''
   ``Whereas the leadership may be at warfare with Pan Am, the rank
and file are completely loyal to the company,'' Kriendler said.
``It is not in their hearts to turn their backs on their
customers.''
   Any workers taking part in that warfare would face ``discipline
in the severest form,'' he added.
   Negotiations began late Saturday night at the request of a
federal mediator, and continued for six hours past the midnight
strike deadline. When talks broke off Sunday morning, Teamsters
leaders said that union members _ reservation clerks, customer
service agents and other clerical staff _ would continue to work.
   The talks resumed at 3 p.m. at Pan Am headquarters in Manhattan,
but recessed about a half-hour later when the company rejected the
mediator's call for arbitration, according to Genoese.
   The federal mediator involved in the negotiations, Walter C.
Wallace, said after the talks broke off that he had asked both
sides to re-evaluate their positions.
   The Federal Mediation Board ``will stay in touch with the
parties, and there will be a resumption of negotiations at an early
and appropriate time,'' Wallace said.
   ``I have been involved in negotiations where there have been
shootings and bombings ... and I am still involved in
negotiations'' with the antagonistic parties, he said.
   The labor dispute involves Pan Am's attempts to cut costs by $35
million through concessions by the Teamsters. The ailing airline
needs labor concessions totaling $540 million over the next three
years, company officials have said.
   Asked about the major points of contention, Pan Am spokesman
Jeff Kriendler said, ``Let's say that the company long ago
established a $35 million objective of achieving cost reductions.
What is negotiable is how we reach the $35 million figure.''
   The company does not view the amount itself as negotiable,
Kriendler said, but the union maintains that it is.
   The company has vowed to maintain operations with replacement
workers in the event of a strike. The Transport Workers Union voted
Friday not to support a Teamsters' strike, and pilots, flight
attendants and flight engineers were not expected to honor picket
lines.
   The Teamsters represent workers at airports in Boston, Detroit,
Chicago, Seattle, San Francisco, San Diego, Los Angeles, Honolulu,
Houston, Washington, New York and the Florida cities of Tampa,
Orlando and Miami. The vast majority of the workers are employed in
New York and Miami.
</TEXT>
