<2ND_LINE>AM-UPI, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0042,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New UPI Management Team To Meet Monday With Guild Representatives</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Efforts to ...' to ADD attempts to reach WNW
spokesman; SUBS 9th graf pvs, `A proxy ...' to conform; Also moved
on general newswires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new management team at United Press
International will meet on Monday with representatives of the Wire
Service Guild to discuss the change in leadership at the
money-losing news service.
   Dan Carmichael, a negotiator and guild spokesman, said Sunday
that UPI's new president, Paul Steinle, asked to meet with guild
officials about the transfer of control to World News Wire Group
Inc.
   The union ``wants to see UPI remain an integrated, quality,
competitive general international news service,'' Carmichael said
Sunday.
   Following the meeting, Dr. Earl W. Brian, 45, the chairman of
WNW, and Steinle plan to hold a news conference to discuss the
transition.
   Efforts to reach Brian and Steinle, who assumes direct
operational control of UPI, were unsuccessful Sunday. Telephone
numbers for the two were not available. Calls to the Washington
hotel where WNW spokesman Dwight Geduldig was staying were not
immediately returned.
   Mario Vazquez Rana, a Mexican publisher who paid $41 million to
acquire UPI from Chapter 11 proceedings in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in
June, announced Friday that he had sold control of the company's
stock to the WNW.
   Vazquez Rana granted WNW ``irrevocable proxy'' to operate UPI
for at least 10 years ``in exchange for present and future
financial considerations totaling more than $55 million,'' UPI said
in a statement.
   Under the arrangement, Vazquez Rana gave up all management and
financial obligation for UPI.
   A proxy represents a transfer of voting power represented by the
ownership shares, but not the shares themselves. No stock changed
hands, Geduldig said Saturday.
   Under an earlier agreement with the guild, Vazquez Rana cannot
sell his interest in UPI without first giving the union the right
of first refusal.
   The proxy arrangement enables WNW to take control of UPI without
buying it, but Brian said in an interview in Sunday's New York
Times that he intends to acquire the news agency and will meet with
the union to discuss how that might be done.
   Brian, who also is chairman of Financial News Network, the
24-hour cable television service, was an unsuccessful bidder for
UPI in 1985 and waged a vigorous legal challenge to Vazquez Rana's
efforts to acquire the company.
   Brian, a former surgeon, was California's health and welfare
secretary while President Reagan was governor of the state. He
created Biotech Capital Corp., which changed its name last year to
Infotechnology Inc.
   Brian declined to commit himself to preserving UPI as a general
news service. Union leaders have expressed concern it might be
turned into a specialized service, concentrating, for example, on
business news.
   ``I'm not going in with any commitment other than to turn this
business around,'' Brian told the Times.
   He added that Vazquez Rana's statement that UPI loses $1 million
a month may prove to be a conservative estimate.
</TEXT>
